h-century law-giving Welsh king. The name may also arise from the Breton personal name <i>Houuel</i>, <i>Huwel</i>, <i>Huwal</i>, <i>Howael</i>, cognate with the Welsh name. Bretons were especially numerous in the eastern counties of England. See   Powell  .","English: perhaps from a Middle English personal name <i>Huwel</i> (spelled <i>Howel</i>), a shortening of <i>Huwelot</i> or <i>Huelin</i> (see   Hewlett   and   Huling  ), both pet forms of Middle English <i>Huw</i> (see   Hugh  ).","English: habitational name from Howell (Lincolnshire), from an uncertain initial element + Old English <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’."],"variants":[{"name":"Howle","meanings":["English and Welsh:","variant of   Howell  .","variant of   Hole  ."]},{"name":"Howells","meanings":["English and Welsh (Glamorgan): variant of   Howell  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent English <i>-s</i>.","English: perhaps occasionally a nickname for someone who was fearless, from Middle English <i>houe</i>, <i>houwe</i> ‘anxiety, fear’ (Old English <i>hogu</i> or <i>hoga</i>) + <i>les</i> ‘less’. If this has survived as a modern surname, its pronunciation has been influenced by that of the name in 1 above.","English: variant of   Holes  ."]},{"name":"Powell","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Hywel</i> ‘son of <i>Hywel</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘eminent’ (see   Howell  ).","Irish: mainly of Welsh origin as in 1 above, but sometimes a surname adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Phóil</b> ‘son of the servant of Saint Paul’ (see   Guilfoyle  ).","English: variant of   Paul   or   Poole  ."]}]},{"name":"Daffydd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>David</b> . In widespread use during the Middle Ages, it was later largely replaced by the English form, but since the late 19th century it has come into its own again."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Daffydd ap Hywell was born in 1390, in Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Wales as the son of Hywel ap Jenkin and Elen Banw. He married Nest Verch Hir Gunter in 1415, in Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1450, in Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1390–about 1450":"1390–umbes 1450","1390–1450":"1390–1450","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1415–Female":"1415–Surnud","1419–Female":"1419–Surnud","1415":"1415","1315":"1315","1450":"1450","1419":"1419","1390":"1390","about 1450":"umbes 1450","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1390–about 1450":"1390–noin 1450","1390–1450":"1390–1450","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1315–Female":"1315–Kuollut","1415–Female":"1415–Kuollut","1419–Female":"1419–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1315":"1315","1450":"1450","1419":"1419","1390":"1390","about 1450":"noin 1450","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1390–about 1450":"1390–environ 1450","1390–1450":"1390–1450","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1315–Female":"1315–Décédée","1415–Female":"1415–Décédée","1419–Female":"1419–Décédée","1415":"1415","1315":"1315","1450":"1450","1419":"1419","1390":"1390","about 1450":"environ 1450","Wales, United Kingdom":"Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Daffydd ap Hywell est né en 1390, à Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Galles, fils de Hywel ap Jenkin et Elen Banw. Il a épousé Nest Verch Hir Gunter en 1415, à Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils. Il est décédé environ 1450, à Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 61 ans."},"de":{"1390–about 1450":"1390–um 1450","1390–1450":"1390–1450","–Male":"Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1315–Female"